Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Domingo R Rodgers in court with attorney Valeria Lenise Taylor.  Thomas L. Potter appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy court clerk:  vk   Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant. 
The Court sentenced the defendant to serve  1 YEARS at the House of Corrections with 4 days credit CONSECUTIVE to any other sentence.

Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on 2 YEARS probation.

  Conditions of Probation:
-  60 days condition time with good time credit Huber for work and education.  STRAIGHT TIME.  Court stayed commencement until 9/15/2015
- No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause
- no weapons
- no voting until his civil rights are restored
- 40 hours of community service
- AODA assessment and cooperate with any programs deemed necessary by the probation department.
- No possession/consumption/selling/distribution of illegal drugs/alcohol.
- Random urine screens.
- Obtain HSED/GED
- Obtain/maintain fulltime employment/education/vocation.
- Letter of apology to to Dawn W within 30 days
- No contact with Dawn W or co-defendant:
- Provide a DNA sample.
- Follow all rules of supervision and follow through with any other treatment deemed necessary by the department.

Court ordered the defendant pay all of the following by the end of supervision.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment:
Restitution in the amount of $283.00 to Dawn W; 
DNA surcharge; 
Court waives all other court costs due the imposition of restitution
All applicable fees of supervision.
-  No Cash Bail Posted in this matter

Defendant Domingo R Rodgers in court with attorney Valeria Lenise Taylor.  Thomas L. Potter appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy court clerk:  vk  Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, Addendum and Jury Instructions, received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Information and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm.  Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.
Defendant to provide a DNA sample.  
Filed:  Ineligible Voting Right form.
